roaster_description: Kiaguthu was founded in 1964 and is located in the Karuthi region of Central Nyeri at 1847 meters above sea level, between the Rwarai and Chinga rivers. Kiaguthu is a member of the Othaya Farmers Co-operative Society, which Phil visited at the beginning of this year (2016). Othaya is a very progressive operation, complete with their own dry mill and quality control lab. They are a large co-op with 19 factories (although not all of them operated in the 2016 season, given the smaller crop), but despite their size, they are producing impeccable quality.

roaster_description: This syrupy and sweet espresso blend has been the staple of our lineup since the very beginning. It is a product of intensive lot selection and close, direct work with the farmers who produce its components. Supreme balance and a wonderful sweetness make this a classic.

Organic Black Cat Espresso offers a full-bodied mouthfeel with clean flavors of caramel, honeydew melon, and grape. Sweetness is abundant, finishing with a resonating coating of dark chocolate and toasted almond.

Reclaiming dark roasts from the realm of less-than-great coffee, we take some of our best and roast them with care in Forty-Six to create something complex, sweet, clean, smoky, and nuanced. This coffee was originally recipe #46; hence the name

Big Trouble offers nutty, caramel flavors people know and love, which may seem easy—and our goal is to make it easy to enjoy in any brewer—but it's actually one of the most challenging for us, because clean, sweet, low-acidity coffees from small-scale farms can be elusive.
Hologram is our update of the classic Mocha Java flavor profile. Fruit-forward and chocolatey coffees combine to create something distinctly complex

We pay extra attention to decaf because we know people love it solely for its flavor. For Slow Motion, we start with great coffee—from the same farmers we work with for all of our coffees—and decaffeinate it in small batches using chemical-free water processing.

roaster_description: This organic coffee comes from a naturally occurring forest in the Jimma Zone of Ethiopia. It was grown by Abdul Wahid Sherif on his 1000 hectare farm, which was established in 2009 as a land grant from Ethiopia’s investment agency to protect some of the last remaining dense forest in the country.
Nemba is comprised of several high altitude micro planatations near the Congo-Nile Crest. The cup is balanced with tropical fruit flavours and a tangerine finish.

Grown in what is considered to be the cradle of humanity - Kenya's Rift Valley - this coffee is carefully handpicked and processed near the town of Mairu Kumi by the Mutungati Farmers Cooperative Society.

Guji is a village in the Sidamo region of Ethiopia, around which are grown some of the world's best coffees. This Guji in particular makes an incredibly bright, sweet and clean brew, with flavours of lemon zest, ginger, and brown sugar. One of our favourite origins, a coffee from Guji has made it into our lineup every year since Propeller Coffee's founding.

Our diligent, tried-and-true espresso blend that’s been with us from the start. This steadfast blend is designed to produce a big-bodied shot packed with flavour and complexity that can hold its own when combined with milk.

While we rotate its component parts depending on the season, its defining feature is a fine balance of dark fruit, Swiss chocolate and nutty tones with medium acidity, tailor-made to stand the test of time. This is a Direct Trade coffee.

Our ode to the dark roast done right. This blend is a chance for our roasters to prove their agility as they take the roast to just before or right up to the second crack – a sweet spot that preserves all of the full-bodied smoothness and caramel tones of a dark roast before crossing into bitter, burnt territory.

The composition and roast level changes with the seasons (as with all of our blends), but the roast character will hold steady. For those who crave the weighty intensity of darker roasts, this one’s for you. This is a Direct Trade coffee.

It's always an incredible feeling to taste a coffee at origin, fall in love, then get to do it all over again.  Guji has an amazing chocolate-ginger note upfront with a distinct berry jam vibe in the finish.  Let's just say we have hearts in our eyes for this coffee.

The classic Cut Coffee espresso blend, Butter Knife is steady, sweet and easy to use. The perfect working blend for busy shops looking for a versatile espresso. 

Butter Knife is designed to perform as a rich, jammy, stand-alone espresso but also blends perfectly with milk to produce nutty, sweet, creamy drinks. 

Relying on crops from a group of interconnected Brazilian farms ensures Butter Knife is consistent and fresh all year round.

Peanut butter, berry jam and toffee

roaster_description:
Highlighting the best of what's in season In Bloom is an ever-changing espresso blend focused on freshness and sweetness. 

More fruit-forward than the traditional Butter Knife espresso, In Bloom is an exciting, complex espresso on its own that rounds out with caramel sweetness in milk drinks. 

Currently, half of In Bloom comes from the Werka Station in Sidama. It is juicy and floral, mixing jasmine with a burst of melon. It is in conversation with Vista Al Bosque from Hoja Blanca. Wilmar Castillo has owned the farm for 18 years with his wife and son. It is a creamy and sweet cup that mixes vanilla with cooked plum and the satisfying depth of root beer. In Bloom remains a seasonally dynamic 50/50 blend that is always sweet, juicy and clean.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Fudge sundae with pralines and raspberries

roaster_description:
The second offering in our Honduras direct trade program originates from Nelson Ramirez. He is a third generation farmer who runs Finca Chely. It sits high in the mountains above Lake Yojao. Cool fog rises from the water creating lower temperatures and slowing cherry growth. After processing, Ramirez uses beneficio San Vincente in Pena Blanca for milling and transport. 

The extended maturation combines with Ramirez's expertise in an extraordinarily clean cup. It opens with a slight tropical and berry acidity, landing between mango and black currant. The cup is smooth and nutty, with creamy hazelnut and praline flavours. The finish is long with stewed fruit and just a hunt of spice - think of a slice of warm apple pie.

Entry number nine in our Women Producers series comes from Codech or the Coordinator of Organizations for the Development of Concepcion Huista. 

We last had Codech in 2015, but this offering specifically comes from women-owned or managed member farms. Through the premium, paid over the fair trade base, the program splits funding between health-initiatives and farming infrastructure. 

Few coffees can compete with a late harvest Guatemala. They are sweet, sticky, and heavy with chocolate. Codech opens with a sparkling burst of raspberry. It rounds out thick with heavy cream before going full chocolate. The finish is long with black cherry and candied almond notes.

We love well-processed and well-roasted decaf. This seasonal crop comes from selected farms in the Quindio Department. 

Freshly harvested beans are lightly steamed and then washed with ethyl acetate, which is derived from the natural fermentation of sugar cane and fruit. 

Decaf is the first roast of the day and because it can be very sensitive, we cycle the roaster to half of its typical energy levels. This ensures the delicate tropical fruit flavours of banana and the deep chocolate cake notes remain intact. 

Our motto : Long live decaf and death before dark roast.

Grown to the east of Mount Kenya, coffees from Embu County offer a unique profile from other Kenyan coffees.  Known for their heavy and velvety body, coffees from this region showcase darker fruits, browning sugars, and a rounder, more balanced acidity.

Bear Hug Espresso is our answer to those who want a heavier and richer coffee without crossing over to the dark side. Our plump bear is a sweet beast who spends most days sauntering through the berry buffet line. Some days you just need a hug.

Grown at 1725 mail, Nereo's coffee is a fully washed Villa Sarchi varietal processed by his neighbours at Helsar de Zarcero. The micro mill works closely with about 40 such coffee farmers in the West Valley region of Costa Rica to process their coffees and create micro lots so they can forge relationships with buyers.

The Eshete station is located in the town of Sede, which is in the Yirgacheffe district of the Gedeo Zone. The station is owned and run by Alemayu Yirdaw, Gizaw Alemayu, and Wondosen Alemayu.

This is a multi-producer lot from Cusillo, which is in the La Union municipality at the northern edges of the Narino Department. Formerly known as the La Union Cooperative, the reborn FUDAM Producers Association represents the small lot farmers that dot the area's high peaks. After wet processing at FUDAM, crops travel north towards Quindio for dry milling at the Armenia station.
A single-origin filter coffee for the people. Extremely sweet. Beautifully balanced.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Extremely sweet, beautifully balanced, always delicious

roaster_description: La Campanella is De Mello Palheta’s Holiday Mainstay! Now in its 4th edition, the goal of this coffee is to fill every cup with warmth and cheer.  Whether you’re brewing cup after cup for your family, friends, and loved ones, or keeping it all to yourself, we hope you get to enjoy a cup of this in front of a fire or cuddled up on the couch as the soft snow falls outside your window.

This is a very exciting coffee for us to share, as it was purchased without reliance on the ever dominant Oromia union. Typically, for small roasters to purchase coffee from Ethiopia, we’re constrained to buying from large scale importers who purchase whole containers through the Oromia Union. As such, it can be very difficult for us to trace back exactly which Farmer’s Coopertive Union (FCU) produced the coffee, being left to operate with only the washing station name.

Thanks to the incredible work of Shared Source, they were able to work directly with the Sor Geba FCU which represents another 147 co-ops, and narrow down their purchase to two lots from the Dika Gabe washing station. This means that we have the ability to next year not only return to the washing station but to the specific lots from each co- op to potentially purchase from the exact same lot once again. This is almost a complete impossibility for small scale roasters, and represents a new frontier in Ethiopian coffee production that we at De Mello are super excited to share in.

Coffee proccessed at Dika Gabe are grown in accordance with traditional, and now legally mandated, organic cultivation methods in which other crops like false banana are interplanted with coffee trees in order to maintain healthy soil. Additionally, the Dika Gabe Co-op is a Technoserve supported Co-op, an initiative that aims to increase the profitability and sustainability of Ethiopia agricultural commodities like coffee.

This means they benefit from training and information sessions on improving coffee quality through processing and also receive an eco-pulper for demuciligation of coffees that uses significantly less water, a serious bonus in a country facing consistent drought conditions.

On top of all of this, the coffee is incredible in quality, one of our favourite ever washed Ethiopians. Its incredibly sweet and smooth, with a thick peach jam mouth feel and red fruit notes that linger beautifully well after the cup is finished!

It’s been 4 years since we’ve had a natural processed coffee. So, since it’s been that long, we wanted this one to be spectacular. Back in January, when our buyer was cupping the latest harvest in Addis, this natural processed lot of Gedeb from the Adinew family was particularly delicious. 

METAD is a third-generation family owned business with land in the Guji and Sidama zones. What’s really impressive about METAD is their commitment to their local community. With educational opportunities including university scholarships and sponsorship for a state-of-the-art elementary school with more than 700 students, and healthcare for employees - METAD is a positive presence. 

METAD is also expanding an Out-grower program designed to provide technical assistance, share modern farming equipment, and provide certification programs for more than 5,000 local farmers who are paid premiums for their cherry and second payments after coffee is sold.

Walking through La Colmena back in February, our green buyer tells us she couldn’t wipe the silly grin off her face. There was just SO. Much. Coffee. This year’s harvest is a true milestone for Arturo, who has been working tirelessly for the past few years to convert his farm to operating as Organic Certified. It’s a topic dear to his heart, and it’s always a favourite thing to talk about, usually chatting about what we are growing in our respective vegetable gardens back home in Peña Blanca, and in Vancouver, BC, as we wind up the foothills of Cielito in his truck.

We wish we could take you all to this farm. The pickers are visibly happy, a few with earbuds in, listening to Aventura (think Backstreet boys of Latin America), growing, singing along while picking deep crimson/purple Caturra and Catuai.  

We could tell you how much work Arturo puts into making sure his coffee is sweet as honey (hence the name, which means “The Beehive”). We could also tell you, how his focus on soil health has produced his tastiest lot to date with a whopping 50 bag harvest (Triple of what he normally produces), but instead, We think you should just try this coffee for yourselves.

Even back in February, and certainly in May when the bulk of the harvest was ripe, we knew that this coffee would be our Holiday filter lot for 2017. - Happy Holidays!

Gigessa is a washing station owned by Faysel Abdosh, located in Shakiso in the south. The volumes coming out of this new (2014) washing station are already impressive, producing well over 10 containers of both washed and natural process. This particular lot is a Grade 1 that really stood out to our buyer when she was cupping countless lots back in Addis in January at the tail end of harvest season. 

The terroir of this area is special and among the highest grown coffees in the country. Heirloom varieties of surrounding forest are transferred to family smallholder plots over time and make up the flavour profile of this region. 

This marks our first Guji release of the season, and you bet we have a couple more vibrant intense lots from the south to tuck into as the weather cools down.

La Bendción had an excellent harvest this year! They bounced back from leaf rust damage in a commendable way, with a return to full production, and one of the highest yields they have had. Ramon was ruthless with his pruning a few years ago, and with a few harvests to recover, the coffee is not only producing well, but the crop is healthier than it’s ever been - this means loads of sweetness.

Through the past few years, we were still showing our unwavering support as partners, still buying the small amounts that Ramon was able to produce. This is an important part of the story, because if he wasn’t able to sell his small yields at specialty prices a couple years back, it’s possible we wouldn’t see this full and wonderful return to normalcy - which in Ramon’s case is producing the vibrant, articulate, and sweet coffee you have in your cup today.

We are thrilled to offer La Bendicion as our signature Holiday Espresso for the season. The creamy texture, coupled with a sweetness that reminds us of pineapple cake is perfect for warming up fireside.

roaster_description: Decaf with oomph! Roasted dark for a lively taste and CO2/water processed too.

High altitude Andean grown coffee, smoky and sweet - but with an attitude.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Strawberry, lemon, honey, black tea, passionfruit
roaster_description: Ethiopia sees its coffee production as a national issue, providing government-affiliated exchanges that oversee the grading and selling. But at its root, Ethiopia’s coffee is made by small farmers and Torea comes to us from a small group of farmers near the Torea village, Abaya district in the Yirgacheffe region of SNNPR. This Ethiopian heirloom varietal is grown at 1700 meters above sea level and washed in a wet mill in spring water. This lends to a light cup with a very unique strawberry and lemon taste with a sharp passionfruit finish that we think you will find it a very refreshing filter coffee.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Stone Fruit, Toffee, Apple, Syrupy, Sweet and Lingering
Fresh Berries, Caramel and White Chocolate
Stone fruit, molasses, spice, syrupy, sweet, lingering
roaster_description:
Santa Lucía is a pristine tract of canopy rain forest on the side of an old volcanic mountain, named for Ricardo’s eldest daughter. Santa Lucia is the gem of the Barrantes operation, along with their coffee mill which they call Helsar de Zarcero; owned and operated by Ricardo Perez Barrantes who has over 30 years of experience in growing coffee. Ricardo and his team have developed the expertise and understand the nuances of processing the coffee seed in order to achieve its highest levels of quality.


To us at Transcend, Santa Lucia is a gem of a coffee. Not only because the coffee is exceptionally delicious year after year, or because the area surrounding the farm is stunning, but because the people behind it are some of the most genuinely passionate and progressive we’ve met in coffee. Ricardo Perez Barrantes started growing coffee here in 1986 with a commitment to environmentally sustainable production. He was among the first in the West Valley to start his own micro-mill, and see the potential to include coffee growers from his surrounding community.

Being the progressive growers that they are, Ricardo’s daughter Mariana visited Canada to learn about coffee roasting and espresso making with a desire to better understand how Santa Lucia is perceived by Canadian consumers. This means that between growing and roasting this coffee has gotten better every year we’ve bought from them.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Maple syrup, raisin, spice, creamy, almond
roaster_description: Don Gregorio Gomez grew coffee on his 5 hectares of land until he passed away earlier this year. For years he brought his harvested cherries to the Bella Vista mill in Antigua, and his coffee was of such a consistently high quality that his coffee was kept as separate lots. Other coffees from around the Agua volcano that are processed at Bella Vista are blended together under the name Hunapu. We have bought coffee from this area for years, but this was the first year buying Don Gregorio’s coffee on its own. Transcend’s Green Buyer, Josh Hockin, decided to keep it separate because it was so delicious when he cupped it. We were very saddened to hear about his passing, but look forward to working with his son, Doroteo, who has taken over managing his land.

Windrush is a medium-sized Estate (400 acres of coffee) on the very high and steep slopes of Kiambu County. The estate is famed for its exceptional tea and coffee growing – in fact it is the only estate remaining in Kenya that exclusively farms the most traditional of Kenyan varietals: SL28.

Altitudes reach well over 2200 masl where the tea grows, and coffee production averages an altitude of 1750masl. The Windrush/Yara Estates are among the oldest remaining estates in Kenya. In 1971 ownership was transferred from the original White Kenyan owners to Indigenous peoples, in line with land reforms across the country from the 1950s. The estates are now managed by locals trading as the Gatatha Farmers Co. Ltd.

Windrush itself is quite distinct in the Kenyan landscape – colder and wetter with lush riverine valleys, plenty of dams and ancient fig trees – and as such possesses a healthier, more drought resistant ecosystem. Great farm management practices include digging soil pits to retain rain water and prevent erosion and planting blue grass as ground cover for the same reason.

Processing is the traditional Double Fermentation in which cherries go through a disc depulper, and parchment coffee is fermented in traditional concrete tanks before washing and and then being returned for the second fermentation or soaking, overnight.

The clean coffee is the then moved to skin drying beds overnight, before raised- bed sun drying for a nice seven days.

We managed to secure this lot, and the AB, via the auction system – in our experience the most robust, transparent and fair way to ensure the farmer receives the highest price possible and that there is full traceability for the buyer and the producer.

We've purchased several times from Mierisch Farms, the iconic and perhaps revolutionary Nicaraguan estate farm run by Doc Mierisch and his family. This particular coffee we were drawn to trying due to its innovative processing. We're always looking for new processing forms to see what they can do to change the flavour of a coffee. We spoke with Erwin, Doc's son, who runs the day to day operations about how exactly this process work, and he gave us a few notes. 

“The coffee cherry is brought down from the farm (intact), where we have selected the ripest cherries, to the dry mill. Once at the dry mill we keep the cherries in the sack, and we sprinkle it with some water. We then allow a certain amount of controlled fermentation of the cherry. We are always keen to be monitoring the cherries during this time.

This could take around 24 to 36 hours, and the cherries are monitored constantly. Once you can see, and smell, that the cherries have reached the point of the most intense fruitiness. We then lay the cherries out on the patio, and we allow it to sun dry until it has an optimal humidity of 12%.

All lots are then placed in a well ventilated, and fresh, warehouse so that the beans can rest for a period of around 30 days, before it is finally shipped off.”

Doc Mierisch, returned to Nicarauga after a career as a doctor in America with the intention of revitalizing the farm and pushing forward coffee quality. In the resulting years, Mierisch farms has grown to be known world-wide as one of the best producers of Nicaraguan coffee. Along with experimental processing, they’ve also grown an incredible range of varieties from Pacamara to Javanica to the more common varietals, like this one, Bourbon.

Anibal Red Honey comes to us from Carlos Montero and his family in Tarrazu, Costa Rica. They operate two farms, and process all of the coffee through a micro-mill they’ve named Don Eli after Carlos’s late father, Don Eli Montero.

Now in its third generation of coffee farmers, the Montero family branched out into producing specialty grade coffee in the 2014/2015 harvest, a risky move that has already paid great dividends. Carlos’s goal was to achieve a better regulation of his coffee but also to experiment with more innovative processing methods. In so doing, they left behind the mass production concept they’d followed in the past, trading it in for a “quality over quantity” mindset. He’s also been working to institute sustainable practices in his farms, including a focus on organic certification for his whole farm while running a single nano lot that has been chemical-free for years.

While Carlos oversees soil quality and cherry selection, his son Jacob oversees the wet-milling and depupling processes, key components in the production of quality honey processed coffees. His two daughters, Mariajose and Marianela are also closely involved with the farm. Mariajose is only 17 but tends to the African drying beds, monitoring moisture levels and raking the beans hourly. Marianela, handles the logistics and shipping and is currently working to assist other farmers in their regions to access the specialty coffee market.

Red Honey Process: Anibal Red Honey is created by depulping and washing the cherries, while leaving about seventy percent of the mucilage behind. The beans are then left in a thin layer on raised beds to dry for between 15 and 20 days.

It’s a steady, medium-bodied, dependable foundation for your daily routine. Simple, but never basic.

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Smooth and balanced, with fruity and floral notes

roaster_description: We’ve always had the number three on our side here at Bluebarn, so it didn’t come as a real shock when, after countless espresso tasting sessions (and so many shots we could hear colour), we found our winning espresso in a blend of thirds. This blend changes with the seasons, and these days, it's made up of nearly equal parts Brazil, Ethiopian, and Guatemala coffees. Smooth and balanced, with fruity and floral notes, each component is roasted separately to bring out its unique characteristics before being blended. We can’t wait to wake up every morning and pull ourselves a shot. It’s killer any way you make it, from a ristretto to a latte, so the fun part is deciding how to drink it.

This blend is vibrant and rich with notes of bing cherry, cane sugar and a lingering, saccharine ﬁnish.

Evolve is the culmination of our efforts to create the ultimate balance of sweetness, complexity and transparency. The goal of this blend is to maintain all of the incredible qualities unique to espresso while still showcasing the vibrant and tantalizing flavours of top level coffees. The beans that comprise this blend will change on occasion in order to emphasize seasonality and nothing but the freshest and highest quality coffees will be chosen.

As months go by and new, fresh coffees arrive, different flavours will emerge. However, our guiding principals will remain the same: sweet, rich and downright delicious espresso. This blend will never be sour or underdeveloped and will always pair terrifically with milk. We’re so incredibly proud of Evolve and we can’t wait for you to try it out!

roaster_tasting_notes_string: Dark chocolate, roasted almond, caramel, syrupy, full body
roaster_description: The Fifth Avenue blend carries the namesake of our Roastery location on West 5th Avenue in Mount Pleasant. Our Roastery is where it all begins; it is the foundation of the whole company.  It's where we decide on our flavour profiles and meticulously test each new coffee.  Fifth Avenue blend represents this foundation.  It's a strong and full bodied coffee with dark chocolate notes that add depth, providing this espresso with the strength to act as the base in any beverage, from a single shot espresso, building to a rich, milky latte. Our intention with this blend was to create a coffee that would sit on the other end of the spectrum from the No. 3 blend. The simple yet intense flavours of our Fifth Avenue blend yield a low acidity coffee which offers a super smooth and syrupy texture.  This blend is a staple for us, and it goes down a treat.

We are proud to present our first offering from our Direct Trade relationship with Finca Nueva Armenia. Located in the rocky canyons of Huehuetenango, the farm is nestled in a valley between two peaks of the Sierra Madre mountain range and has been cultivated by four generations of the Recinos family.

 Currently in charge are twins jorge and javier recinos leonardo. Having both studied environmental engineering, they share a belief in preserving the environment. Biodiversity is a huge focus at the farm. The plantation is only cleaned with machetes and hoes, to preserve the local flora and fauna. When the two brothers took over in 1996 they applied for and received an organic certification and the farm has been cultivated and managed organically since then. They have since received a bird friendly certification from the smithsonian migratory bird center.

The coffee fields of this farm range from 1200-1500 meters above sea level and include several varieties. For our first offering, we have chosen to showcase their Red Bourbon. We found this coffee sweet, floral and clean, with notes of almond cookie and red grape.

Banko Gotiti is a washing station owned and operated by METAD Agricultural Development PLC. The family-run company was gifted property by Emperor Selassie in honor of the matriarch, Muluemebet Emiru, the first African female pilot. METAD is now managed by her grandson Aman Adinew, and its export partner Rift Valley Trading LLC is operated by his brother Michael Adinew. Among the many important pieces of work undertaken by METAD are their commitment to equal employment opportunities for women and education opportunities for the youth of the coffeelands, their early partnerships with Grounds for Health, and their development of Africa’s first SCAA certified lab.

We find Gedeb coffees similar in style to Yirgacheffes, but a little bigger, a little bolder, a little less subtle. This exceptional lot fits that mold, offering abundant notes of stone fruit, citrus, and berries layered with plenty of inherent sweetness and that slightly floral, slightly savory je ne sais quoi that makes washed Ethiopian coffees some of the most unique and thrilling in the world.

Our most popular coffee offering is back, and better than ever!

Every coffee lot is unique in its own way, but we want to celebrate the classic coffee flavor profiles of our favorite coffee origins, and right there at the top is coffees from Yirgacheffe in Ethiopia.

Coffees from Yirgacheffe are the melding of ancient Ethiopian coffee varieties with more modern processing techniques. What results is the best-of-both-worlds burst of complex flavors with clean, balanced overall character that we love in these coffees.

Floral, citrusy, clean, complex, balanced. It doesn't get much better than this!

After a long winter in 2015, as we waited for the flowers to bloom, we worked on a new blend. The idea was to create a coffee that maintained the complex fruit flavours we love in Butterfly Kiss but with a gentler, rounder finish. We paired washed Ethiopian coffees with the nutty chocolate notes inherent in Central American coffees and, as the flowers finally began to bloom, the name came to us: Sakura, or cherry blossom in Japanese.

roaster_description: Maybe you’ve experienced the Butterfly Kiss before, the gentle tickling of eyelashes against eyelashes. We wanted a blend that would capture the essence of this loving and warm gesture within the cup. Made completely of naturally processed Ethiopian coffees, each sip explodes with sweet fruit flavours and leaves a lingering tickle – the Butterfly Kiss – on your tongue.

Cette petite récolte propose un café sucré, un corps similaire au thé, accompagné de notes florales de gardenia et de rose. Le grué de cacao, l’eau de coco, le melon et les saveurs de kumquat accompagnent l’expérience, suivi par une finale de pistache. C’est un café unique, peut-être pas pour tout le monde, mais nous l’aimons et nous avons hâte de le partager avec vous.
Le résultat final est un café particulièrement citronné, rehaussé de notes de thé noir, de caramel et une viscosité veloutée ainsi qu’une finale de mélasse.

Pour ce qui est du café transformé de façon naturelle, il s’agit d’un café possédant un caractère fruité subtil et on apprécie également l’absence d’arrière-goût de fermentation ou d’alcool que l’on pourrait retrouver dans les cafés naturels de moins bonne qualité. Il a le goût de prunes et de framboises avec une finale agréablement franche et sucrée.

En plus de la qualité du café, son processus de fermentation complexe lui donne un profil unique. Des notes indéniables de pain d’épice et de pain grillé à la cannelle font partie de ses marques distinctives, suscitant l’unanimité à notre session de sélection.

This coffee is exactly what I love about washed Columbian coffees; clean, sweet, and balanced. When hot, hot lemon tea, praline, and vanilla dominate the flavour notes. The sweetness is pronounced, with a mellow lemony citric acidity, and a luscious candied nuttiness in the finish. As the coffee cools, the acidity becomes juicier, like pink lemonade and navel orange juice, along with a syrupy date-like sweetness. The finish is long and complex, with a cacao nib and roasted barley nuttiness.

product_name: Brazil Fazenda Rainha Yellow Bourbon Pulped Natural
roaster_tasting_notes_string: This coffee is an interesting one to taste for sure. There is so much going on, and even more as it cools. When hot, peanut brittle, sugarcane, and warm baking spices dominate, with undertones of tabacco and dried cherry. The gentle stone fruit acidity is complementary towards the rich syrupy mouthfeel. As it cools, the peanut brittle becomes more like peanut punch, the sugarcane sweetness intensifies, reminding me of freshly pressed sugarcane juice, and the cherry undertone comes alive, reminding me of maraschino cherry. The finish of this coffee is long, with a mild green tea tannic dryness combined with raw cacao.

Right off the bat, there is an intense blackcurrant aroma. When hot, the blackcurrant translate into the flavour, along with a cranberry jelly tartness, and a roasted plum stonefruit sweetness. As it cools, the malic acidity becomes more apparent, along with a citric blood orange acidity. The blackcurrant becomes Ribena (blackcurrent juice concentrate), along with a foresty herbal note like black sage, and lemongrass in the finish.
